FBIS3-27724 "dreas020_a_94008" FBIS-EAS-94-020 Document Type:Daily Report 31 January 1994 NORTHEAST ASIA Japan Aftermath of Political Reform Accord Reported LDP, SDPJ Approve Compromise OW2901060594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0553 GMT 29 Jan 94 OW2901060594 Tokyo KYODO Language: English Article Type:BFN [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 29 KYODO -- The main opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and the Social Democratic Party [of Japan] (SDP) [SDPJ] on Saturday [29 January] endorsed a compromise over political reform reached between Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and LDP President Yohei Kono, officials of the parties said. The LDP reached the accord at a meeting of the highest decision-making body of the Executive Council and the SDPJ, the largest force in the seven-party ruling coalition, at a meeting of members of both houses of the Diet. Hosokawa and Kono reached a basic accord Friday night in eleventh-hour talks to break the impasse over the government-proposed political reform bills on which Hosokawa had staked his political career.
